Introduction
Command Line Interfaces (CLI) can be challenging at first but offer speed and efficiency. For example, you can find your IP address much faster using CLI than through the graphical interface. CLI uses fewer system resources and allows easier automation and remote management.
Learning Objectives
This guide focuses on teaching how to use Windows Command Prompt cmd.exe to:
Display system information
Troubleshoot network configurations
Manage files and folders
Monitor running processes

What is the default command line interpreter in the Windows environment?
Answer: cmd.exe

Basic System Information
ver: Shows the operating system version.
systeminfo: Provides detailed system info like OS, processor, and memory.
driverquery | more: Lists installed drivers, showing one page at a time.
help: Displays help for specific commands.
cls: Clears the command prompt screen.
